Guidelines and Benchmarks

A guideline is similar to a standard but not mandatory. It's a recommendation that should likely be followed but is not necessarily required. Security benchmarks are a measure of an organization's baseline of security performance, improvements over time, and comparisons against industry peers. 

Benchmarks and guidelines are documented guides that offer prescriptive guidance for establishing a secure baseline configuration for different systems. Usually, they are created by volunteers and non-profit entities to contribute to the security community. They come in different shapes and address multiple technologies. For example, the Open Web Application Security Project OWASP created a secure coding guide to protect web applications.
 


Another popular benchmark is the Center of Internet Security (CIS), which provides a secure configuration baseline for many systems such as Windows, Linux, and firewalls. We will see how to use CIS benchmarks to harden different systems in the upcoming lab.
 

Figure - zoom in


Finally, the Cloud Security Alliance (CSA) created the "Security Guidance for Critical Areas of Focus in Cloud Computing." A practical, actionable roadmap for organizations seeking to adopt the cloud paradigm, helping with secure transition and operation in the cloud.
 

CSA Security Guidance - zoom in


When implementing these guidelines, you should know that a single configuration change may break your network. So, it's vital to research provided recommendations, understand the implications of each control, and test drive it in a simulated lab before pushing it to production.

Although benchmarks and guidelines are not mandatory to enforce, they can dramatically improve the organization's overall security posture, giving it a notable boost. These guidelines were of great help to us throughout the years and were at the top of our security recommendations for organizations seeking improved resilience. We witnessed dozens of advanced attacks mitigated because of one of the security controls in these guidelines. Benchmarks are gold!
